<node CREATED="1566553719058" ID="ID_1377454751" MODIFIED="1566553719058" TEXT="Context-Free Grammars. A context-free grammar (CFG) is a set of recursive rewriting rules (or productions) used to generate patterns of strings. A CFG consists of the following components: a set of terminal symbols which are the characters of the alphabet that appear in the strings generated by the grammar." />
</node>
<node CREATED="1566553719058" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_1566479452" LINK="https://www.tutorialspoint.com/automata_theory/context_free_grammar_introduction" MODIFIED="1566553719058" TEXT="Context-Free Grammar Introduction - tutorialspoint.com">
<node CREATED="1566553719058" ID="ID_71826660" MODIFIED="1566553719058" TEXT="Definition &#226;&#710;&#8217; A context-free grammar (CFG) consisting of a finite set of grammar rules is a quadruple (N T P S) where. N is a set of non-terminal symbols. T is a set of terminals where N &#226;&#710;&#169; T = NULL. P is a set of rules P: N &#226;&#8224;&#8217; (N &#226;&#710;&#170; T)* i.e. the left-hand side of the production rule P does have any right context or left context." />
</node>
<node CREATED="1566553719058" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_1065017743" LINK="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/context-free" MODIFIED="1566553719058" TEXT="Context-free | Definition of Context-free by Merriam-Webster">
<node CREATED="1566553719058" ID="ID_80614218" MODIFIED="1566553719058" TEXT="Context-free definition is - of relating to or being a grammar or language based on rules that describe a change in a string without reference to elements not in the string; also : being such a rule." />
</node>
<node CREATED="1566553719058" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_758320257" LINK="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/6713240/what-is-a-context-free-grammar" MODIFIED="1566553719058" TEXT="regex - What is a Context Free Grammar? - Stack Overflow">
<node CREATED="1566553719058" ID="ID_239548647" MODIFIED="1566553719058" TEXT="Each book provides a formal description of a context-free grammar which is a type of formal grammar then states and proves basic theorems about context-free grammars required to understand them (such as the pumping lemma for context-free languages and conversion and normal form theorems)." />
</node>
<node CREATED="1566553719058" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_23297299" LINK="https://brilliant.org/wiki/context-free-grammars/" MODIFIED="1566553719058" TEXT="Context Free Grammars | Brilliant Math  Science Wiki">
<node CREATED="1566553719058" ID="ID_1018927736" MODIFIED="1566553719058" TEXT="Context-free grammars (CFGs) are used to describe context-free languages. A context-free grammar is a set of recursive rules used to generate patterns of strings. A context-free grammar can describe all regular languages and more but they cannot describe all possible languages. Context-free grammars are studied in fields of theoretical computer science compiler design and linguistics." />
</node>
<node CREATED="1566553719058" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_1319874772" LINK="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Context-sensitive_grammar" MODIFIED="1566553719058" TEXT="Context-sensitive grammar - Wikipedia">
<node CREATED="1566553719058" ID="ID_1359015821" MODIFIED="1566553719058" TEXT="A context-sensitive grammar (CSG) is a formal grammar in which the left-hand sides and right-hand sides of any production rules may be surrounded by a context of terminal and nonterminal symbols.Context-sensitive grammars are more general than context-free grammars in the sense that there are languages that can be described by CSG but not by context-free grammars." />
</node>
